liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Senator Hume asks Bullock to expand on what factors are driving services inflation (or the rising price of services). Bullock replies that it comes back to inputs like electricity costs, rents, wages — they all have an impact on the price of services, which impact inflation.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What elements are driving services inflation?

children.content: Senator Hume asks Bullock to expand on what factors are driving services inflation (or the rising price of services).
Bullock replies that it comes back to inputs like electricity costs, rents, wages — they all have an impact on the price of services, which impact inflation.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: After some procedural matters to open this morning's Senate estimates hearings, the RBA has got right into being questioned and not having an opening statement. Senator Jane Hume opened the questions, asking Michele Bullock for her first impressions on yesterday's inflation data. She said inflation was a little higher than the RBA had expected. "The print came out a little higher than we'd been forecasting at our August statement on monetary policy but it was pretty much where we thought it would come out, given the information we'd come into since then, particularly the monthly CPI indicator, so we thought it was going to be about where it came out." She mentioned the impact of fuel prices was no surprise.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Inflation 'a little bit higher' than RBA had forecast, Bullock says

children.content: After some procedural matters to open this morning's Senate estimates hearings, the RBA has got right into being questioned and not having an opening statement.
Senator Jane Hume opened the questions, asking Michele Bullock for her first impressions on yesterday's inflation data.
She said inflation was a little higher than the RBA had expected.

"The print came out a little higher than we'd been forecasting at our August statement on monetary policy but it was pretty much where we thought it would come out, given the information we'd come into since then, particularly the monthly CPI indicator, so we thought it was going to be about where it came out."
She mentioned the impact of fuel prices was no surprise.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Is there anywhere we can watch the Senate Estimates live today? - Mina. Yes, Mina! Go to the Australian Parliament House website and there's a section called "Watch, Read, Listen" on the front page. That lists all the hearings and action on a given day. Here's a link to today's hearing, which starts at 9.00am AEDT.
